<h3>Pull quotes</h3>

<p>Pull quotes intended to quote something from the flow of the article in a larger size to draw the reader into the article. This is typically different in purpose to a blockquote where you want to include a longish quotation in the flow of the narrative. Additionally, these pull quote elements have links to share on twitter and facebook.</p>

<p><strong>Context:</strong> <code>&lt;div class="long-form-content"&gt;</code></p>

<pre><code>
&lt;p class="pull-quote" data-quote="(quote-to-tweet; 140 chars)"&gt;(quote-to-display)&lt;/p&gt;
</code></pre>

<p>The <em>quote-to-display</em> is obviously not optional, however the <em>quote-to-tweet</em> in the <code>data-quote</code> attribute is optional. If the <code>data-quote</code> attribute is left blank, then the quote for the tweet will be created automatically based on the <em>quote-to-display</code> truncated to tweet length with an ellipsis (if appropriate). This could mean that the quote might be truncated in a non-optimal location, so for more control use the <code>data-quote</code> attribute to specify exactly what you want tweeted.</p>

